. 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[299,494,1284,1306]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nipponica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[299,494,1284,1306]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pherusa nipponica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[503,564,1284,1306]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[503,564,1284,1306]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Posterior end with long chaetae, chaetae about as long as body width, shorter terminally (
<figureCitation box="[1217,1307,1499,1524]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1118,1140]" captionTargetBox="[173,1411,196,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-310@27.[169,1417,193,1097]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 9. Pherusa neopapillata Hartman, 1961. A. Holotype (LACM 531), lateral view. B. Paratype (LACM 532), anterior end, dorsal view, some sand particles removed. C. Same, chaetiger 11, notochaetae. D. Same, chaetiger 6, right parapodium, neurochaetae. E. Same, chaetiger 27, right parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 0.8 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 0.4 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951934/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
); pygidium conical, truncate, anus slightly projected, whitish, without cirri.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Remarks.</emphasis>
As indicated in the key above, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[682,896,1571,1596]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nipponica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[682,896,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pherusa nipponica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[905,970,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[905,970,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Muller, 1776)" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[1100,1399,1571,1596]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plumosa">
<emphasis box="[1100,1224,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. plumosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Muller, O. F." box="[1241,1391,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref49681" refString="Muller, O. F. (1776) Zoologiae Danicae Prodromus, seu Animalium Daniae et Norvegiae indigenarum. Characteres, nomina et synonyma imprimis popularium. Hallageriis, Havniae (Copenhagen), 274 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13268" type="book" year="1776">Müller, 1776</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
by having body papillae covered by only fine sediment particles. There are two main differences between these two species: the number of transverse series of papillae per segment, and the shape (and colour) of their neurohooks. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[151,290,1680,1703]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nipponica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[151,290,1680,1703]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. nipponica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[296,358,1679,1704]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[296,358,1679,1704]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
there are 3–4 series, and neurohooks are yellowish to brown and markedly curved, whereas in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plumosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. plumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are 6–8 transverse series of papillae, and neurohooks are brownish and only slightly falcate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1751,1776]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the original name of the country, 
<collectingCountry box="[1098,1185,1751,1776]" name="Japan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Nippon</collectingCountry>
, with a suffix to fit the gender of the generic name, meaning Japanese.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
